---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PostCard from '../components/PostCard.astro';
import { getBlogPosts } from '../utils/getPosts';

const allBlog = await getBlogPosts();
// Mirror the "Book Reviews" column on the home page — pulls posts whose
// category is anything we'd consider learning-related.
const homeschoolPosts = allBlog
	.filter((p) => ['Homeschool', 'Education', 'Books', 'Book Reviews'].includes(p.data.category))
	.slice(0, 4);
---

<BaseLayout
	title="Homeschool"
	description="A rich, immersive education for kids who are meant to think deeply and live faithfully."
>
	<article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 md:py-24">
		<!-- Hero -->
		<div class="mb-16 text-center md:mb-20">
			<div
				class="bg-primary/10 text-primary mb-6 inline-flex h-16 w-16 items-center justify-center rounded-2xl"
			>
				<svg
					xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
					class="h-8 w-8"
					viewBox="0 0 20 20"
					fill="currentColor"
				>
					<path
						d="M10.394 2.08a1 1 0 00-.788 0l-7 3a1 1 0 000 1.84L5.25 8.051a.999.999 0 01.356-.257l4-1.714a1 1 0 11.788 1.838L7.667 9.088l1.94.831a1 1 0 00.787 0l7-3a1 1 0 000-1.838l-7-3zM3.31 9.397L5 10.12v4.102a8.969 8.969 0 00-1.05-.174 1 1 0 01-.89-.89 11.115 11.115 0 01.25-3.762zM9.3 16.573A9.026 9.026 0 007 14.935v-3.957l1.818.78a3 3 0 002.364 0l5.508-2.361a11.026 11.026 0 01.25 3.762 1 1 0 01-.89.89 8.968 8.968 0 00-5.35 2.524 1 1 0 01-1.4 0zM6 18a1 1 0 001-1v-2.065a8.935 8.935 0 00-2-.712V17a1 1 0 001 1z"
					></path>
				</svg>
			</div>
			<h1 class="font-display mb-4 text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight md:text-6xl">
				Homeschool
			</h1>
			<p class="text-base-content/70 mx-auto max-w-2xl text-2xl leading-tight md:text-3xl">
				A rich, immersive education for kids who are meant to think deeply and live faithfully.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Our Approach (Revised Opening) -->
		<div class="prose prose-lg mb-16 max-w-none">
			<h2>Our approach</h2>
			<p>We’re not trying to recreate a classroom inside an RV.</p>
			<p>
				We’re trying to give our children a deep, uncommon education — one built on Christ,
				strengthened by books, shaped by real places, and widened by hands-on learning.
			</p>
			<p>
				We draw from classical education, living books, read-alouds, writing, observation, unit
				studies, and practical skills. We think of it as a Renaissance-style education: broad enough
				to awaken curiosity, disciplined enough to build skill, and rooted enough to form character.
				By that, we mean we want our kids exposed to many disciplines — literature, history,
				science, theology, art, music, economics, nature, and practical skills — because the world
				is connected.
			</p>
			<p>Jesus is the cornerstone upon which we build everything.</p>
		</div>

		<!-- What It Actually Looks Like -->
		<div class="mb-16">
			<h2 class="font-display mb-6 text-3xl font-bold">What it actually looks like</h2>

			<div class="prose prose-lg mb-8 max-w-none">
				<p>
					We’ve been homeschooling for 12 years, and full-time RVing while homeschooling for nearly
					3. Our kids are 4, 7, 10, and 12. My wife handles the core academics. I focus on the
					extras — art, identification hikes, projects, and deeper dives.
				</p>
				<p>
					Our weeks are adaptable. Some days we knock out several lessons. Other days one subject
					takes the whole morning. The older two are becoming more self-directed, which helps.
					Moving days are extremely disruptive — we’ve learned to expect very little those days and
					just survive.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="border-base-300 bg-base-200 rounded-2xl border p-8">
				<h3 class="mb-4 text-xl font-semibold">A typical rhythm (when we’re not moving)</h3>
				<ul class="text-base-content/90 space-y-3">
					<li><strong>Mornings:</strong> Core subjects (math review, reading, writing, history)</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Reading Fridays:</strong> My wife reads aloud for hours — historical fiction, biographies,
						living books
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Hikes &amp; identification:</strong> We hike several times a week for exercise and
						learning — plants, trees, mushrooms, animal tracks
					</li>
					<li><strong>Afternoons:</strong> Art, projects, unit studies, or free time</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Screen time:</strong> Limited to once a weekend — we protect play and real learning
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Evenings:</strong> Prayer together, read-alouds, honest conversations about what’s
						hard
					</li>
				</ul>
				<p class="text-base-content/70 mt-6 text-sm italic">
					This isn’t rigid. Some weeks are beautiful. Some weeks are survival mode. That’s real life
					with four kids on the road.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- What We Are Not Trying to Do (NEW) -->
		<div class="bg-base-200 mb-16 rounded-3xl p-8 md:p-10">
			<h2 class="font-display mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">What we are not trying to do</h2>

			<div class="text-base-content/80 mx-auto max-w-md space-y-3">
				<p>We are not trying to make every hike into a worksheet.</p>
				<p>We are not trying to turn the RV into a perfect classroom.</p>
				<p>We are not trying to pretend our kids are always eager learners.</p>
				<p>We are not trying to follow one homeschool philosophy perfectly.</p>

				<p class="text-base-content pt-3 font-medium">
					We are trying to build a faithful, rigorous, flexible education that fits real family
					life.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- Core Practices -->
		<div class="mb-16">
			<h2 class="font-display mb-6 text-3xl font-bold">What we actually do</h2>

			<div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="border-base-300 rounded-2xl border p-6">
					<div class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">Immersive history &amp; unit studies</div>
					<p class="text-base-content/80 text-sm">
						When we’re near a historic site, we often tie it into a unit study. We read historical
						fiction before we go and talk about it afterward. Learning sticks better when it’s
						connected to real places.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="border-base-300 rounded-2xl border p-6">
					<div class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">Nature &amp; observation on the trail</div>
					<p class="text-base-content/80 text-sm">
						We hike for health and learning. The kids identify plants, trees, mushrooms, and animal
						tracks. We encourage journaling and writing about what they notice — practice over
						polish.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="border-base-300 rounded-2xl border p-6">
					<div class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">Strong core academics</div>
					<p class="text-base-content/80 text-sm">
						We take math, writing, history, economics, theology, and the sciences seriously. We
						review current grade + one grade behind. Our oldest is starting essay writing. We don’t
						treat science and faith as enemies. We believe the created world is orderly, knowable,
						and full of evidence of God’s wisdom.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="border-base-300 rounded-2xl border p-6">
					<div class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">Faith &amp; character formation</div>
					<p class="text-base-content/80 text-sm">
						We pray together, read Scripture together, and make space for honest conversations.
						Character matters more than perfect academics.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- What We Use -->
		<div class="mb-16">
			<h2 class="font-display mb-6 text-3xl font-bold">What we actually use</h2>

			<div class="prose prose-lg mb-8 max-w-none">
				<p>
					We keep a small core and lean heavily on the library. We’re not loyal to any brand. We
					keep what works and drop what doesn’t.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
				<div class="border-base-300 rounded-2xl border p-6">
					<div class="mb-2 font-semibold">Core programs we’re using right now</div>
					<ul class="text-base-content/90 space-y-2 text-sm">
						<li><strong>Sonlight</strong> — Our main spine for history, literature, and Bible</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Horizons Math</strong> — Challenging, but we’re reconsidering it because the explanations
							are hard for the kids to follow independently
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>The Good and the Beautiful</strong> — Used as a supplement for language arts and
							other subjects
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Classical Conversations</strong> — We’ve drawn from the classical model for years
							and are planning to participate more formally this summer for memory work and community
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>

				<div class="border-base-300 rounded-2xl border p-6">
					<div class="mb-2 font-semibold">Other tools we rely on</div>
					<ul class="text-base-content/90 space-y-2 text-sm">
						<li>Library cards (heavy use — we’re there constantly)</li>
						<li>Historical fiction tied to the places we visit</li>
						<li>Nature identification guides (plants, trees, mushrooms, tracks)</li>
						<li>Art supplies and project materials</li>
						<li>Read-alouds (my wife’s specialty)</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>

			<p class="text-base-content/70 mt-6 text-sm italic">
				We recently dropped a few things that weren’t working well. We’re always tweaking. That’s
				part of the process.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- An Honest Note -->
		<div class="bg-base-200 mb-16 rounded-3xl p-10 text-center">
			<h2 class="font-display mb-4 text-2xl font-bold">An honest note</h2>
			<p class="text-base-content/80 mx-auto max-w-lg">
				Homeschooling is hard. Some weeks feel like we’re crushing it. Other weeks we’re just
				surviving. Moving days destroy momentum. Curriculum decisions are never final. But we
				believe this path is giving our kids something rare and valuable — and we’re committed to
				it.
			</p>
			<p class="text-base-content mt-6 font-medium">
				If you’re thinking about homeschooling, especially on the road: you can do it too. It won’t
				look perfect. But it can be rich, meaningful, and deeply formative.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Live posts pulled from the homeschool / books / education categories.
		     Mirrors the rv-life.astro pattern so all category landing pages behave
		     the same. Replaces the previous fully-static layout. -->
		{
			homeschoolPosts.length > 0 ? (
				<div class="mb-16">
					<div class="mb-8 flex items-baseline gap-4">
						<span class="eyebrow">From the blog</span>
						<span class="border-base-content/15 flex-1 border-t" />
						<a
							href="/category/Homeschool/"
							class="font-display text-base-content/60 hover:text-primary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase transition-colors"
						>
							All homeschool posts →
						</a>
					</div>
					<div class="grid gap-8 sm:grid-cols-2">
						{homeschoolPosts.map((post) => (
							<PostCard kind="blog" entry={post} />
						))}
					</div>
				</div>
			) : (
				<div class="border-base-300 mb-16 rounded-2xl border p-8 text-center">
					<p class="font-display mb-2 text-lg font-bold">Homeschool posts coming soon</p>
					<p class="text-base-content/70 text-sm">
						Living-books reviews, road-school routines, and unit-study how-tos. Subscribe below to
						catch them when they land.
					</p>
				</div>
			)
		}

		<!-- Final CTA -->
		<div class="text-center">
			<p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4">Want to follow how this actually works in real time?</p>
			<a href="/#newsletter" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg"> Follow our journey </a>
		</div>
	</article>
</BaseLayout>
